SIMPLE: scumbling
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scumbling
<hw>Scum"bling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fine
Arts)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A mode of obtaining a softened effect, in
painting and drawing, by the application of a thin layer of opaque color
to the surface of a painting, or part of the surface, which is too
bright in color, or which requires harmonizing.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>In crayon drawing, the use of the stump.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The color so laid on. Also used
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shining above the brown <qex>scumbling</qex> of leafless
orchards.</q> <rj><qau>L. Wallace.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scummer</ent>⟦br⟧
